<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

<head>
<title>@HI{{masu}}-forms</title>
<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="japanese.css"/>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
</head>

@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{masu}}-forms" grammar="@HI{{masu}}-forms"}}

<body>

<h1>@HI{{masu}}-forms</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @FORMATION{{@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{masu}}}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{masenn}}}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{mashita}}}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{masendeshita}}}}
<li> @FORMATION{{@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{mashou}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
Formation of the basic @HI{{masu}}-stem is described <a href="grammar-verb-formation-masu.html">here</a>.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
A verb in the @HI{{masu}}-form works as a predicate and also makes a sentence polite.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha@KJ{{every^day^exertion^strong}}shimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I study every day.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The @HI{{masu}}-form is also used to describe habitual actions.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{every^morning}}6@KJ{{time}}ni@KJ{{rouse}}kimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I wake up at 6AM every morning.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
To form a question add @HI{{ka}} to the end of the sentence. The word order is otherwise unchanged.
To answer such a question, the verbs are repeated. @HI{{soudesu}} and @HI{{soujanai}} cannot be used.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{every^morning}}@KJ{{what^time}}ni@KJ{{rouse}}kimasuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{6@KJ{{what^time}}ni@KJ{{rouse}}kimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      What time do you get up every morning?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I get up at 6AM.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
There is no future conjugation in Japanese. Instead the context makes places a sentence in the future.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ashita6@KJ{{time}}ni@KJ{{rouse}}kimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'll get up at 6AM tomorrow.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
To form the past conjugation of the @HI{{masu}}-form, drop @HI{{masu}} and replace it with @HI{{mashita}}.
This form corresponds to the plain past <a href="grammar-verb-formation-ta.html">@Vta{{}}</a>.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kesa6@KJ{{time}}ni@KJ{{rouse}}kimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I got up at 6AM this morning.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
To form the past negative conjugation of the @HI{{masu}}-form, drop @HI{{masu}} and replace it with @HI{{masenndeshita}}.
This form corresponds to the plain past negative @HI{{nakatta}}, 
where the plain past form, <a href="grammar-verb-formation-nai.html">@HI{{nai}}</a>, has been conjugated into the
past as an <a href="adjectives.html">@HI{{i}}-adjective</a>.
<p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="mashou">To</a> form the volitional of the @HI{{masu}}-form, drop @HI{{masu}} and replace it with @HI{{mashou}}.
This form corresponds to the plain volitional <a href="grammar-verb-formation-volitional.html">@Vyou{{}}</a>.
In a volitional sentence, if the subject is explicitly stated it is marked with @HI{{ga}} and the implication is
that the stated subject, rather than anyone else, will perform the action.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{chotto@KJ{{rest}}mimashou.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Let's have a break.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The volitional is used to invite the listener to do something with the speaker.
It is also used to respond poitively to such an invitation. Note that an invitation using
<a href="grammar-masen-ka.html">@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{masenka}}</a> shows more consideration for the listener than using
@Vmasustem{{}}@HI{{mashou}} as the former explictly allows for a negative reply.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{isshouni@KJ{{daytime}}gohanwo@KJ{{eat}}bemasenka}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{ee,@KJ{{eat}}mashou.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: Won't you have lunch with me?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: yes, let's go and eat.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The question forms of sentences are answered by repeating the same verb. @HI{{soudesu}} <em>cannot</em> be used.
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

